{
  "texts": [
    "To generate answers from the models, we resorted to the two alternative strategies found in the literature (see Appendix B.3 for details about these strategies).",
    "The first is called 'full answer generation' (FA).",
    "Every time it is prompted, the model is free to generate a number of tokens sufficient to cover all possible valid answers, producing a single answer that may be invalid or require post-processing.",
    "The second strategy is called \"next-token probability\" (NTP), where at each prompt the model is asked to generate only the single next token, in the form of a probability distribution over the thousands of tokens embedded in the LLM.",
    "Theoretically, with a temperature of 1 and perfect model compliance of NTP, the probability distributions yielded by FA should converge towards those of NTP, given enough FA generations for each profile."
  ]
}